features:

Single Instance: Ensures only one object of the class exists in the JVM.
Global Access Point: Provides a centralized way to access the instance.
Lazy or Eager Initialization: An Instance can be created at class load time (eager) or when first needed (lazy).
Thread Safety: Can be designed to work correctly in multithreaded environments.
Resource Management: Useful for managing shared resources like configurations, logging or database connections.


Race condetion--> In a multi-threaded environment, the basic implementation of the Singleton Design Pattern may fail due to a problem known as a Race condition
In a multi threaded environment when multile threads are accesing the same instence it can lead to creating of multiple threads. which voilates the core principle of singleton.

To prevent this issue, you can use synchronization to ensure that only one thread can access the method that creates the instance at a time. Here is an example of a thread-safe Singleton implementation in Java:

```java
public class Singleton {
    private static volatile Singleton instance;
    private Singleton() {} // Private constructor to prevent instantiation
    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) { // Check if instance is null
            synchronized (Singleton.class) { // Synchronize on the class object
                if (instance == null) { // Double-check if instance is still null
                    instance = new Singleton(); // Create the instance
                }
            }
        }
        return instance; // Return the singleton instance
    }
}
```
In this implementation, the `getInstance()` method checks if the `instance` is null. If it is, it synchronizes on the `Singleton.class` to ensure that only one thread can execute the block of code that creates the instance. The double-checking of `instance == null` inside the synchronized block ensures that if multiple threads reach the first check at the same time, only one will create the instance, while the others will see that the instance has already been created and will return it. This approach effectively prevents the race condition and ensures that only one instance of the Singleton class is created, even in a multi-threaded environment.